SIMPLE: tucker
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tucker
<hw>Tuck"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who,
or that which, tucks; specifically, an instrument with which tuck are
made.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A narrow piece of linen or the like, folded across
the breast, or attached to the gown at the neck, forming a part of a
woman's dress in the 17th century and later.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[See <er>Tuck</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, 4.]</ety>
<def>A fuller.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[Cf. <er>Tuck</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 5.]</ety>
<def>Daily food; meals; also, food in general.</def> <mark>[Slang or
Colloq.]</mark></p>

<p><q>Tobacco, matches, and <qex>tucker</qex>, the latter comprising
almost anything within the province of food.</q> <rj><qau>C. L.
Money.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tucker</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tucker
<hw>Tuck"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To tire; to weary; -- usually
with <ptcl>out</ptcl>.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tucket</ent>⟦br⟧
